request_template.md",".github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/bug-report.md",".github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/improvement-request.md",".github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/config.yml",".github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/feature-request.md",".editorconfig","README.md","MANIFEST.in","docs/_assets/banner.png","docs/_assets/apiflask-logo.png","CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md","NOTICE","CONTRIBUTING.md","CHANGES.md","LICENSE","codecov.yml","docs/_assets/favicon.png","docs/_assets/swagger-ui.png","docs/_assets/redoc.png","docs/_assets/execute.png","docs/_assets/extra.css","docs/changelog.md","docs/configuration.md","docs/authors.md","docs/_assets/try-it-out.png","docs/_assets/white-logo.png","docs/comparison.md","docs/api/route.md","docs/api/schema_adapters.md","docs/api/exceptions.md","docs/api/commands.md","docs/api/fields.md","docs/api/openapi.md","docs/api/helpers.md","docs/api/blueprint.md","docs/api/schemas.md","docs/api/security.md","docs/api/app.md","docs/api/validators.md","docs/api-docs.md","docs/authentication.md","docs/_templates/main.html","docs/migrations/flask.md","docs/migrations/flask-restplus.md","docs/migration_guide.md","docs/request.md","docs/contributing.md","docs/docs.md","docs/openapi.md","docs/index.md","docs/error-handling.md","docs/examples.md","examples/README.md","examples/auth/apikey_auth/app.py","examples/auth/token_auth/app.py","examples/auth/multi_auth/app.py","examples/auth/basic_auth/app.py","docs/usage.md","docs/schema/pydantic.md","docs/schema/index.md","docs/schema/marshmallow.md","docs/response.md","docs/tips.md","examples/base_response/marshmallow/app.py","examples/base_response/pydantic/app.py","examples/dataclass/app.py","examples/blueprint_tags/app.py"],"durationMs":16,"numFiles":100,"truncated":true}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_8c28204dde4542bf91774102","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t\n2\t![](https://apiflask.com/_assets/apiflask-logo.png)\n3\t\n4\t# APIFlask\n5\t\n6\t[![Build status](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions/workflows/tests.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions) [![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=2CFPCZ1DMY)](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask)\n7\t\n8\tAPIFlask is a lightweight Python web API framework based on [Flask](https://github.com/pallets/flask). It's easy to use, highly customizable, ORM/ODM-agnostic, and 100% compatible with the Flask ecosystem.\n9\t\n10\tAPIFlask supports both [marshmallow](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow) schemas and [Pydantic](https://docs.pydantic.dev/) models through a pluggable schema adapter system, giving you the flexibility to choose the validation approach that best fits your project.\n11\t\n12\tWith APIFlask, you will have:\n13\t\n14\t- More sugars for view function (`@app.input()`, `@app.output()`, `@app.get()`, `@app.post()` and more)\n15\t- Automatic request validation and deserialization\n16\t- Automatic response formatting and serialization\n17\t- Automatic [OpenAPI Specification](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification) (OAS, formerly Swagger Specification) document generation\n18\t- Automatic interactive API documentation\n19\t- API authentication support (with [Flask-HTTPAuth](https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/flask-httpauth))\n20\t- Automatic JSON response for HTTP errors\n21\t\n22\t\n23\t## Requirements\n24\t\n25\t- Python 3.9+\n26\t- Flask 2.1+\n27\t\n28\t\n29\t## Installation\n30\t\n31\tFor Linux and macOS:\n32\t\n33\t```bash\n34\t$ pip3 install apiflask\n35\t```\n36\t\n37\tFor Windows:\n38\t\n39\t```bash\n40\t> pip install apiflask\n41\t```\n42\t\n43\t\n44\t## Links\n45\t\n46\t- Website: <https://apiflask.com>\n47\t- Documentation: <https://apiflask.com/docs>\n48\t- 中文文档: <https://zh.apiflask.com/docs>\n49\t- PyPI Releases: <https://pypi.python.org/pypi/APIFlask>\n50\t- Change Log: <https://apiflask.com/changelog>\n51\t- Source Code: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask>\n52\t- Issue Tracker: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/issues>\n53\t- Discussion: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/discussions>\n54\t- 中文论坛: <https://codekitchen.community>\n55\t- Twitter: <https://twitter.com/apiflask>\n56\t- Open Collective: <https://opencollective.com/apiflask>\n57\t\n58\t\n59\t## Donate\n60\t\n61\tIf you find APIFlask useful, please consider [donating](https://opencollective.com/apiflask) today. Your donation keeps APIFlask maintained and evolving.\n62\t\n63\tThank you to all our backers and sponsors!\n64\t\n65\t### Backers\n66\t\n67\t[![](https://opencollective.com/apiflask/backers.svg?width=890)](https://opencollective.com/apiflask)\n68\t\n69\t### Sponsors\n70\t\n71\t[![](https://opencollective.com/apiflask/sponsors.svg?width=890)](https://opencollective.com/apiflask)\n72\t\n73\t## Example\n74\t\n75\t```python\n76\tfrom apiflask import APIFlask, Schema, abort\n77\tfrom apiflask.fields import Integer, String\n78\tfrom apiflask.validators import Length, OneOf\n79\t\n80\tapp = APIFlask(__name__)\n81\t\n82\tpets = [\n83\t    {'id': 0, 'name': 'Kitty', 'category': 'cat'},\n84\t    {'id': 1, 'name': 'Coco', 'category': 'dog'}\n85\t]\n86\t\n87\t\n88\tclass PetIn(Schema):\n89\t    name = String(required=True, validate=Length(0, 10))\n90\t    category = String(required=True, validate=OneOf(['dog', 'cat']))\n91\t\n92\t\n93\tclass PetOut(Schema):\n94\t    id = Integer()\n95\t    name = String()\n96\t    category = String()\n97\t\n98\t\n99\t@app.get('/')\n100\tdef say_hello():\n101\t    # returning a dict or list equals to use jsonify()\n102\t    return {'message': 'Hello!'}\n103\t\n104\t\n105\t@app.get('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n106\t@app.output(PetOut)\n107\tdef get_pet(pet_id):\n108\t    if pet_id > len(pets) - 1:\n109\t        abort(404)\n110\t    # you can also return an ORM/ODM model class instance directly\n111\t    # APIFlask will serialize the object into JSON format\n112\t    return pets[pet_id]\n113\t\n114\t\n115\t@app.patch('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n116\t@app.input(PetIn(partial=True))  # -> json_data\n117\t@app.output(PetOut)\n118\tdef update_pet(pet_id, json_data):\n119\t    # the validated and parsed input data will\n120\t    # be injected into the view function as a dict\n121\t    if pet_id > len(pets) - 1:\n122\t        abort(404)\n123\t    for attr, value in json_data.items():\n124\t        pets[pet_id][attr] = value\n125\t    return pets[pet_id]\n126\t```\n127\t\n128\t<details>\n129\t<summary>You can use Pydantic models for type-hint based validation</summary>\n130\t\n131\t```python\n132\tfrom enum import Enum\n133\t\n134\tfrom apiflask import APIFlask, abort\n135\tfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n136\t\n137\tapp = APIFlask(__name__)\n138\t\n139\t\n140\tclass PetCategory(str, Enum):\n141\t    DOG = 'dog'\n142\t    CAT = 'cat'\n143\t\n144\t\n145\tclass PetOut(BaseModel):\n146\t    id: int\n147\t    name: str\n148\t    category: PetCategory\n149\t\n150\t\n151\tclass PetIn(BaseModel):\n152\t    name: str = Field(min_length=1, max_length=50)\n153\t    category: PetCategory\n154\t\n155\t\n156\tpets = [\n157\t    {'id': 0, 'name': 'Kitty', 'category': 'cat'},\n158\t    {'id': 1, 'name': 'Coco', 'category': 'dog'}\n159\t]\n160\t\n161\t\n162\t@app.get('/')\n163\tdef say_hello():\n164\t    return {'message': 'Hello, Pydantic!'}\n165\t\n166\t\n167\t@app.get('/pets')\n168\t@app.output(list[PetOut])\n169\tdef get_pets():\n170\t    return pets\n171\t\n172\t\n173\t@app.get('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n174\t@app.output(PetOut)\n175\tdef get_pet(pet_id: int):\n176\t    if pet_id > len(pets) or pet_id < 1:\n177\t        abort(404)\n178\t    return pets[pet_id - 1]\n179\t\n180\t\n181\t@app.post('/pets')\n182\t@app.input(PetIn, location='json')\n183\t@app.output(PetOut, status_code=201)\n184\tdef create_pet(json_data: PetIn):\n185\t    # the validated and parsed input data will\n186\t    # be injected into the view function as a Pydantic model instance\n187\t    new_id = len(pets) + 1\n188\t    new_pet = PetOut(id=new_id, name=json_data.name, category=json_data.category)\n189\t    pets.append(new_pet)\n190\t    return new_pet\n191\t```\n192\t\n193\t</details>\n194\t\n195\t<details>\n196\t<summary>Or use <code>async def</code></summary>\n197\t\n198\t```bash\n199\t$ pip install -U \"apiflask[async]\"\n200\t```\n201\t\n202\t```python\n203\timport asyncio\n204\t\n205\tfrom apiflask import APIFlask\n206\t\n207\tapp = APIFlask(__name__)\n208\t\n209\t\n210\t@app.get('/')\n211\tasync def say_hello():\n212\t    await asyncio.sleep(1)\n213\t    return {'message': 'Hello!'}\n214\t```\n215\t\n216\tSee <em><a href=\"https://flask.palletsprojects.com/async-await\">Using async and await</a></em> for the details of the async support in Flask 2.0.\n217\t\n218\t</details>\n219\t\n220\tSave this as `app.py`, then run it with:\n221\t\n222\t```bash\n223\t$ flask run --debug\n224\t```\n225\t\n226\tNow visit the interactive API documentation (Swagger UI) at <http://localhost:5000/docs>:\n227\t\n228\t![](https://apiflask.com/_assets/swagger-ui.png)\n229\t\n230\tOr you can change the API documentation UI when creating the APIFlask instance with the `docs_ui` parameter:\n231\t\n232\t```py\n233\tapp = APIFlask(__name__, docs_ui='redoc')\n234\t```\n235\t\n236\tNow <http://localhost:5000/docs> will render the API documentation with Redoc.\n237\t\n238\tSupported `docs_ui` values (UI libraries) include:\n239\t\n240\t- `swagger-ui` (default value): [Swagger UI](https://github.com/swagger-api/swagger-ui)\n241\t- `redoc`: [Redoc](https://github.com/Redocly/redoc)\n242\t- `elements`: [Elements](https://github.com/stoplightio/elements)\n243\t- `rapidoc`: [RapiDoc](https://github.com/rapi-doc/RapiDoc)\n244\t- `rapipdf`: [RapiPDF](https://github.com/mrin9/RapiPdf)\n245\t\n246\tThe auto-generated OpenAPI spec file is available at <http://localhost:5000/openapi.json>. You can also get the spec with [the `flask spec` command](https://apiflask.com/openapi/#the-flask-spec-command):\n247\t\n248\t```bash\n249\t$ flask spec\n250\t```\n251\t\n252\tFor some complete examples, see [/examples](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/tree/main/examples).\n253\t\n254\t\n255\t## Relationship with Flask\n256\t\n257\tAPIFlask is a thin wrapper on top of Flask. You only need to remember the following differences (see *[Migrating from Flask](https://apiflask.com/migrations/flask/)* for more details):\n258\t\n259\t- When creating an application instance, use `APIFlask` instead of `Flask`.\n260\t- When creating a blueprint instance, use `APIBlueprint` instead of `Blueprint`.\n261\t- The `abort()` function from APIFlask (`apiflask.abort`) returns JSON error response.\n262\t\n263\tFor a minimal Flask application:\n264\t\n265\t```python\n266\tfrom flask import Flask, request\n267\tfrom markupsafe import escape\n268\t\n269\tapp = Flask(__name__)\n270\t\n271\t@app.route('/')\n272\tdef hello():\n273\t    name = request.args.get('name', 'Human')\n274\t    return f'Hello, {escape(name)}'\n275\t```\n276\t\n277\tNow change to APIFlask:\n278\t\n279\t```python\n280\tfrom apiflask import APIFlask  # step one\n281\tfrom flask import request\n282\tfrom markupsafe import escape\n283\t\n284\tapp = APIFlask(__name__)  # step two\n285\t\n286\t@app.route('/')\n287\tdef hello():\n288\t    name = request.args.get('name', 'Human')\n289\t    return f'Hello, {escape(name)}'\n290\t```\n291\t\n292\tIn a word, to make Web API development in Flask more easily, APIFlask provides `APIFlask` and `APIBlueprint` to extend Flask's `Flask` and `Blueprint` objects and it also ships with some helpful utilities. Other than that, you are actually using Flask.\n293\t\n294\t\n295\t## Credits\n296\t\n297\tAPIFlask starts as a fork of [APIFairy](https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/APIFairy) and is inspired by [flask-smorest](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/flask-smorest) and [FastAPI](https://github.com/tiangolo/fastapi) (see *[Comparison and Motivations](https://apiflask.com/comparison)* for the comparison between these projects).\n298\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"00179536-e488-4c8a-a193-df3ba70f62d7","uuid":"c1d790d6-b25a-4509-82ff-8caec2129bd9","timestamp":"2026-04-07T09:30:17.480Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md","content":"\n![](https://apiflask.com/_assets/apiflask-logo.png)\n\n# APIFlask\n\n[![Build status](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions/workflows/tests.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/actions) [![codecov](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask/branch/main/graph/badge.svg?token=2CFPCZ1DMY)](https://codecov.io/gh/apiflask/apiflask)\n\nAPIFlask is a lightweight Python web API framework based on [Flask](https://github.com/pallets/flask). It's easy to use, highly customizable, ORM/ODM-agnostic, and 100% compatible with the Flask ecosystem.\n\nAPIFlask supports both [marshmallow](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow) schemas and [Pydantic](https://docs.pydantic.dev/) models through a pluggable schema adapter system, giving you the flexibility to choose the validation approach that best fits your project.\n\nWith APIFlask, you will have:\n\n- More sugars for view function (`@app.input()`, `@app.output()`, `@app.get()`, `@app.post()` and more)\n- Automatic request validation and deserialization\n- Automatic response formatting and serialization\n- Automatic [OpenAPI Specification](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification) (OAS, formerly Swagger Specification) document generation\n- Automatic interactive API documentation\n- API authentication support (with [Flask-HTTPAuth](https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/flask-httpauth))\n- Automatic JSON response for HTTP errors\n\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Python 3.9+\n- Flask 2.1+\n\n\n## Installation\n\nFor Linux and macOS:\n\n```bash\n$ pip3 install apiflask\n```\n\nFor Windows:\n\n```bash\n> pip install apiflask\n```\n\n\n## Links\n\n- Website: <https://apiflask.com>\n- Documentation: <https://apiflask.com/docs>\n- 中文文档: <https://zh.apiflask.com/docs>\n- PyPI Releases: <https://pypi.python.org/pypi/APIFlask>\n- Change Log: <https://apiflask.com/changelog>\n- Source Code: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask>\n- Issue Tracker: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/issues>\n- Discussion: <https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/discussions>\n- 中文论坛: <https://codekitchen.community>\n- Twitter: <https://twitter.com/apiflask>\n- Open Collective: <https://opencollective.com/apiflask>\n\n\n## Donate\n\nIf you find APIFlask useful, please consider [donating](https://opencollective.com/apiflask) today. Your donation keeps APIFlask maintained and evolving.\n\nThank you to all our backers and sponsors!\n\n### Backers\n\n[![](https://opencollective.com/apiflask/backers.svg?width=890)](https://opencollective.com/apiflask)\n\n### Sponsors\n\n[![](https://opencollective.com/apiflask/sponsors.svg?width=890)](https://opencollective.com/apiflask)\n\n## Example\n\n```python\nfrom apiflask import APIFlask, Schema, abort\nfrom apiflask.fields import Integer, String\nfrom apiflask.validators import Length, OneOf\n\napp = APIFlask(__name__)\n\npets = [\n    {'id': 0, 'name': 'Kitty', 'category': 'cat'},\n    {'id': 1, 'name': 'Coco', 'category': 'dog'}\n]\n\n\nclass PetIn(Schema):\n    name = String(required=True, validate=Length(0, 10))\n    category = String(required=True, validate=OneOf(['dog', 'cat']))\n\n\nclass PetOut(Schema):\n    id = Integer()\n    name = String()\n    category = String()\n\n\n@app.get('/')\ndef say_hello():\n    # returning a dict or list equals to use jsonify()\n    return {'message': 'Hello!'}\n\n\n@app.get('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n@app.output(PetOut)\ndef get_pet(pet_id):\n    if pet_id > len(pets) - 1:\n        abort(404)\n    # you can also return an ORM/ODM model class instance directly\n    # APIFlask will serialize the object into JSON format\n    return pets[pet_id]\n\n\n@app.patch('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n@app.input(PetIn(partial=True))  # -> json_data\n@app.output(PetOut)\ndef update_pet(pet_id, json_data):\n    # the validated and parsed input data will\n    # be injected into the view function as a dict\n    if pet_id > len(pets) - 1:\n        abort(404)\n    for attr, value in json_data.items():\n        pets[pet_id][attr] = value\n    return pets[pet_id]\n```\n\n<details>\n<summary>You can use Pydantic models for type-hint based validation</summary>\n\n```python\nfrom enum import Enum\n\nfrom apiflask import APIFlask, abort\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, Field\n\napp = APIFlask(__name__)\n\n\nclass PetCategory(str, Enum):\n    DOG = 'dog'\n    CAT = 'cat'\n\n\nclass PetOut(BaseModel):\n    id: int\n    name: str\n    category: PetCategory\n\n\nclass PetIn(BaseModel):\n    name: str = Field(min_length=1, max_length=50)\n    category: PetCategory\n\n\npets = [\n    {'id': 0, 'name': 'Kitty', 'category': 'cat'},\n    {'id': 1, 'name': 'Coco', 'category': 'dog'}\n]\n\n\n@app.get('/')\ndef say_hello():\n    return {'message': 'Hello, Pydantic!'}\n\n\n@app.get('/pets')\n@app.output(list[PetOut])\ndef get_pets():\n    return pets\n\n\n@app.get('/pets/<int:pet_id>')\n@app.output(PetOut)\ndef get_pet(pet_id: int):\n    if pet_id > len(pets) or pet_id < 1:\n        abort(404)\n    return pets[pet_id - 1]\n\n\n@app.post('/pets')\n@app.input(PetIn, location='json')\n@app.output(PetOut, status_code=201)\ndef create_pet(json_data: PetIn):\n    # the validated and parsed input data will\n    # be injected into the view function as a Pydantic model instance\n    new_id = len(pets) + 1\n    new_pet = PetOut(id=new_id, name=json_data.name, category=json_data.category)\n    pets.append(new_pet)\n    return new_pet\n```\n\n</details>\n\n<details>\n<summary>Or use <code>async def</code></summary>\n\n```bash\n$ pip install -U \"apiflask[async]\"\n```\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nfrom apiflask import APIFlask\n\napp = APIFlask(__name__)\n\n\n@app.get('/')\nasync def say_hello():\n    await asyncio.sleep(1)\n    return {'message': 'Hello!'}\n```\n\nSee <em><a href=\"https://flask.palletsprojects.com/async-await\">Using async and await</a></em> for the details of the async support in Flask 2.0.\n\n</details>\n\nSave this as `app.py`, then run it with:\n\n```bash\n$ flask run --debug\n```\n\nNow visit the interactive API documentation (Swagger UI) at <http://localhost:5000/docs>:\n\n![](https://apiflask.com/_assets/swagger-ui.png)\n\nOr you can change the API documentation UI when creating the APIFlask instance with the `docs_ui` parameter:\n\n```py\napp = APIFlask(__name__, docs_ui='redoc')\n```\n\nNow <http://localhost:5000/docs> will render the API documentation with Redoc.\n\nSupported `docs_ui` values (UI libraries) include:\n\n- `swagger-ui` (default value): [Swagger UI](https://github.com/swagger-api/swagger-ui)\n- `redoc`: [Redoc](https://github.com/Redocly/redoc)\n- `elements`: [Elements](https://github.com/stoplightio/elements)\n- `rapidoc`: [RapiDoc](https://github.com/rapi-doc/RapiDoc)\n- `rapipdf`: [RapiPDF](https://github.com/mrin9/RapiPdf)\n\nThe auto-generated OpenAPI spec file is available at <http://localhost:5000/openapi.json>. You can also get the spec with [the `flask spec` command](https://apiflask.com/openapi/#the-flask-spec-command):\n\n```bash\n$ flask spec\n```\n\nFor some complete examples, see [/examples](https://github.com/apiflask/apiflask/tree/main/examples).\n\n\n## Relationship with Flask\n\nAPIFlask is a thin wrapper on top of Flask. You only need to remember the following differences (see *[Migrating from Flask](https://apiflask.com/migrations/flask/)* for more details):\n\n- When creating an application instance, use `APIFlask` instead of `Flask`.\n- When creating a blueprint instance, use `APIBlueprint` instead of `Blueprint`.\n- The `abort()` function from APIFlask (`apiflask.abort`) returns JSON error response.\n\nFor a minimal Flask application:\n\n```python\nfrom flask import Flask, request\nfrom markupsafe import escape\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n@app.route('/')\ndef hello():\n    name = request.args.get('name', 'Human')\n    return f'Hello, {escape(name)}'\n```\n\nNow change to APIFlask:\n\n```python\nfrom apiflask import APIFlask  # step one\nfrom flask import request\nfrom markupsafe import escape\n\napp = APIFlask(__name__)  # step two\n\n@app.route('/')\ndef hello():\n    name = request.args.get('name', 'Human')\n    return f'Hello, {escape(name)}'\n```\n\nIn a word, to make Web API development in Flask more easily, APIFlask provides `APIFlask` and `APIBlueprint` to extend Flask's `Flask` and `Blueprint` objects and it also ships with some helpful utilities. Other than that, you are actually using Flask.\n\n\n## Credits\n\nAPIFlask starts as a fork of [APIFairy](https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/APIFairy) and is inspired by [flask-smorest](https://github.com/marshmallow-code/flask-smorest) and [FastAPI](https://github.com/tiangolo/fastapi) (see *[Comparison and Motivations](https://apiflask.com/comparison)* for the comparison between these projects).\n","numLines":298,"startLine":1,"totalLines":298}}}
